examples.en: The streets are dumb with snow. (A. Tennyson)
By ashen roots the violets blow. (A. Tennyson)
There was no anchor, none, to hold by. (Tennyson)
Sometimes the linnet piped his song. (A. Tennyson)
How dense a fold of danger nets him round. (Tennyson)
Mary sat and thought hard things of Dora. (A. Tennyson)
The thick snow falls on her flake by flake. (A. Tennyson)
We grew the fable of the city where we dwelt. (A. Tennyson)
This would make all women kick against their lords. (A. Tennyson)
Nothing will die, all things will change. (A. Tennyson, Poems, 1830)
He chanted a melody loudly and sweetly. (A. Tennyson, Poet's Song, 1842)
